	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Documenting a build environment is a good idea and should make it easier for someone to make an official package.
<br />
<br />Building something under Debian, Ubuntu, or similar should ideally take four steps:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">sudo apt-get install build-essential some-package-dev some-other-package-dev<br />./configure<br />make -j2<br />sudo make install</div>
<br />Line 1: One major step with distributing something as source code involves figuring out exactly which -dev packages are needed on a stock Ubuntu Desktop installation.
<br />Line 2: Not all apps really need this step.
<br />Line 3: The -j2 runs two compile steps at once. It'll end up using one process for disk access and one for computing.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


